---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="About — MemoryHole">
  <div class="wrap">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      MemoryHole is an autonomous observatory for <strong>silent edits</strong>: changes made
      to published news articles, government pages, and market reporting after publication,
      without any correction notice. Once a day it re-reads every tracked page and records
      what changed.
    </p>

    <h2>How detection works</h2>
    <p>
      Article URLs are discovered from RSS feeds (plus a list of static pages) and each
      article's readable text is extracted with trafilatura, aggressively normalized —
      whitespace, unicode, quotes, boilerplate, timestamps, embed/consent placeholders —
      so that cosmetic HTML churn never registers as an edit. Each page's normalized text is
      snapshotted in git; git history is the archive. New text is diffed word-by-word against
      the previous snapshot.
    </p>

    <h2>Categories and filters</h2>
    <p>
      Every source is tagged with a <strong>country</strong> and a <strong>category</strong> —
      world, politics, business, finance, science, technology, sport, health, culture, or
      government. The feed's filter bar lets you narrow by any of those, by significance
      (see below), by source, or by free-text search; filter state is saved to the URL so a
      filtered view can be bookmarked or shared. <a href="finance/">Finance</a> also gets its
      own page, since a quietly revised price, rate, or percentage is a different kind of
      edit worth watching on its own.
    </p>

    <h2>Severity classification</h2>
    <p>Each detected edit is scored by combining rule-based signals — numbers changed,
      named entities swapped, quotes deleted, paragraphs added or removed, headline
      changes — with semantic similarity from a local sentence-transformers model
      (all-MiniLM-L6-v2). No external API is required. In the finance category, a changed
      price, rate, or percentage is weighted heavily enough that it can't be out-voted by
      an unrelated headline tweak in the same article.</p>
    <ul class="methodology">
      <li><span class="badge COSMETIC">COSMETIC</span> — typos, punctuation, formatting; meaning identical.</li>
      <li><span class="badge MINOR">MINOR</span> — rewording with the same meaning.</li>
      <li><span class="badge FACTUAL">FACTUAL</span> — numbers, names, dates, or market figures changed.</li>
      <li><span class="badge NARRATIVE">NARRATIVE</span> — claims added or removed, headline changed, meaning shifted.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Classification is heuristic. A <em>FACTUAL</em> or <em>NARRATIVE</em> badge means the
      text changed in a way worth a human look — it does not by itself imply bad faith.
      Outlets legitimately update developing stories; the point is that the record of change
      should be public.
    </p>

    <h2>Ethics</h2>
    <ul class="methodology">
      <li>robots.txt is respected; the crawler identifies itself honestly as
        <code>MemoryHoleBot/1.0</code> and fetches at most one page per two seconds per domain.</li>
      <li>Paywalled content is never fetched or stored.</li>
      <li>Only extracted article text needed for diffing is stored, always with attribution
        and a link to the original.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Run your own</h2>
    <p>
      MemoryHole is MIT-licensed and runs entirely on free infrastructure (GitHub Actions +
      Pages). Fork it, edit <code>sources.yaml</code> — tag new sources with a country and
      category — enable Pages, done.
      <a href="https://github.com/dipeshrayg/memoryhole">Source and instructions on GitHub.</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
